=> Model: User, Song, Album, Artist, Playlist

- User
V: id, name, email, password, List<Playlist>
M:

- Song
V: id, title, genre, album, artist, duration

- Album
V: id, title, List<Song>, artist

- Artist
V: id, name, List<Album>

- Playlist
V: id, title, list<Songs>, createdBy

=> Constant: SongStatus, SongType
=> Service: UserManager, MusicRecommender, SongLibrary, MusicPlayer, SpotifyImpl

- UserManger
V: Map<User>
M: addUser, removeUser, authenticateUser, createPlaylist, addSongToPlaylist, removeSongFromPlaylist, deletePlaylist

- SongLibrary
V: Map<Artist>, Map<Album>, Map<Song>
M: addSong, addAlbum, addArtist, searchSong

- MusicPlayer
V: currentSong, CurrentPlaylist, status
M: play, plause, skip, seek

- MusicRecommender
V: user
M: recommendSongs, recommendAlbum, recommendArtist

-SpotifyImppl

* points to note:

1) If you look at the implementation of spotify. When using various service managers you can simply return those managers for easy code
demo; Go through the code given below.

public class MusicStreamingService {
    private final MusicLibrary musicLibrary;
    private final UserManager userManager;
    private final MusicRecommender musicRecommender;

    public MusicStreamingService() {
        musicLibrary = MusicLibrary.getInstance();
        userManager = UserManager.getInstance();
        musicRecommender = MusicRecommender.getInstance();
    }

    public void start() {

    }

    public MusicLibrary getMusicLibrary() {
        return musicLibrary;
    }

    public UserManager getUserManager() {
        return userManager;
    }

    public MusicRecommender getMusicRecommender() {
        return musicRecommender;
    }
}
